(appendix
  :book \"book-of-music\"
  :number 2
  :title \"Debussy and the New Harmony\"
  :short-title \"debussy\"
  :estimated-words 1800
  :composer-verified \"Achille-Claude Debussy, born 22 August 1862, Saint-Germain-en-Laye; died 25 March 1918, Paris. He dropped 'Achille' by 1892 and signed his mature works 'Claude Debussy.'\"
  :philosopher-weave (wittgenstein-late peirce jung)

  :prose
\"When Bach and Rachmaninoff and Chopin write a chord, they are drawing on a harmonic language whose logic goes back to the seventeenth century. Chords have a *function* in that language. A dominant seventh wants to resolve to a tonic. A subdominant leans toward the dominant. A minor chord in the middle of a phrase feels different from a major chord in the same position because of where it points. Chords are grammar; they mean something by where they are going.

Claude Debussy, working in Paris from about 1890 to 1918, took this grammar apart. Not by rejecting the old chords, but by using them without their functional meaning — playing them as *colors*, as sound-events valued for their own sonic weight, rather than as steps in a harmonic argument. When he writes a dominant seventh chord in a Debussy piece, it may or may not resolve to a tonic. It may just sit there, ring, and be replaced by another chord that also sits there. Chords become nouns instead of verbs.

This is the shift that changed twentieth-century music. Everything from jazz voicings (which build on Debussy's stacked ninth and eleventh chords) to film scoring (which uses Debussy's colored chord as a way to evoke atmosphere without narrative) to pop songwriting (which borrows Debussy's parallel motion of chords) traces back to what Debussy figured out. He did not do it alone — Maurice Ravel, Erik Satie, and others were part of the same generation — but Debussy is the one whose harmonic vocabulary the twentieth century found most usable.

# Clair de Lune

The most famous Debussy piano piece is *Clair de Lune*, the third movement of the *Suite bergamasque*. He wrote it around 1890 (when he was twenty-seven) but did not publish the suite until 1905. The title comes from a Paul Verlaine poem, and the piece is a moonlit night in slow, sustained triple meter.

The opening is a slow, chorded melody in D-flat major, marked *Andante très expressif*. What is unusual about it — for the harmonic language of 1890 — is the *voicings*. The melody is doubled at the octave. The chords underneath are ninth chords and thirteenth chords, held with pedal so the sound thickens. In a Chopin nocturne, these ninth chords would be passing tones — decorations of simpler triads. In *Clair de Lune*, they are the actual harmony. Debussy has replaced Chopin's triads with the extended chords that would previously have been called dissonances, and he has used them as if they were the resting places.

The middle section moves into a rocking pattern — the left hand plays a broken chord in triplets over which the right hand lays a simple melody. This texture is close to a Chopin nocturne. But then Debussy takes the texture and lets it drift chromatically through several keys before returning to D-flat. The return is not a strong recapitulation with a resolved tonic. It is a soft dissolve — the piece comes back to where it started, but the coming-back is not celebrated; it is quietly done, and the piece ends on a D-flat major chord that is more colored than final.

# La Cathédrale engloutie

*La Cathédrale engloutie* ('The Sunken Cathedral'), from the first book of Preludes (1910), takes Debussy's technique further. The prelude is inspired by a Breton legend of a cathedral submerged off the coast of the island of Ys, which rises out of the sea at certain times and rings its bells before sinking again.

The piece opens with a series of low, ringing open fifths — bare intervals with no third, no color — played *pp* with pedal. Then a chord in the upper register, another chord, another. The chords move in *parallel motion*: the entire chord slides up or down as a unit, keeping the same interval structure between voices. This parallel motion is one of Debussy's most identifiable techniques and one of the most radical harmonic gestures of the era.

In traditional harmony, moving voices in parallel fifths and octaves is considered a bad move — the voices lose their independence and the harmony sounds thin. Debussy uses parallel motion deliberately, because he wants the voices to *not* be independent. He wants a single harmonic *object* to slide through space. When you hear the opening of *La Cathédrale engloutie*, you hear chords floating up out of the water as one thing. The parallel motion is the *point*.

The middle of the prelude has a section marked *Sonore sans dureté* — resounding without harshness. Chords ring in the middle register, held with pedal, moving slowly. This is the cathedral above water, its bells sounding across the sea. Then the piece descends, the chords soften, and the cathedral sinks back below the surface. The final page returns to the low fifths of the opening, quieter and quieter, until the piece dies away.

# La Fille aux cheveux de lin

*La Fille aux cheveux de lin* ('The Girl with the Flaxen Hair'), also from the first book of Preludes, is short and simple and one of the most-played Debussy pieces on student piano recitals. It is in G-flat major, marked *Très calme et doucement expressif* — very calm and gently expressive.

The tune is a simple modal melody, pentatonic in feel (that is, based mostly on five notes rather than the full seven-note major scale). Modal melody was old — it was the melodic material of medieval church music before major and minor keys took over in the seventeenth century, and it was the melodic material of a great many folk musics around the world that Debussy was interested in.

Debussy learned about non-Western modal music, in part, from hearing a Javanese gamelan ensemble perform at the Paris Universal Exposition of 1889. He was thirty-two and just beginning to write the mature music that would become *Prélude à l'après-midi d'un faune* and *Nocturnes*. The pentatonic and modal writing that shows up in his mature work has roots in that gamelan encounter. He did not imitate gamelan music — his pieces are not gamelan pieces — but the pentatonic and modal harmonic vocabulary he took from listening became part of his language.

*La Fille aux cheveux de lin* uses that vocabulary. The melody is modal; the harmony underneath is gently colored with added seconds and ninths; the whole piece stays in one gentle atmosphere for three minutes and then ends. It is a small, complete thing — like a Chopin nocturne, but with a different harmonic dialect underneath.

# What we can do in Scheme

We can build a small demonstration of parallel chord motion — the Debussy technique.

```scheme
;; A chord type: major seventh chord (root, major third, perfect fifth, major seventh)
(define (maj7 root)
  (list root
        (transpose root 4)   ; major third up
        (transpose root 7)   ; perfect fifth up
        (transpose root 11))) ; major seventh up

;; Play a sequence of maj7 chords in parallel motion, sliding down chromatically
(define (parallel-descent starting-root n)
  (transport/tempo 60)
  (with-dynamics 'p
    (pedal/press)
    (let loop ((root starting-root) (count 0))
      (when (< count n)
        (chord/play (maj7 root) 'quarter)
        (loop (transpose root -1) (+ count 1))))   ; slide one semitone down
    (pedal/release)))

(parallel-descent 'F5 8)
```

The program plays eight major-seventh chords, each a semitone lower than the last. In traditional harmony, this progression is *forbidden* — chords in parallel motion carrying the same intervals move as a block and violate voice-leading rules. In Debussy's harmony, this progression is *the point*. The chords slide through space as one object.

If you listen to the opening of *La Cathédrale engloutie* and then to this small program, you will hear the family resemblance. The specific chords are different; the *technique* is the same. Debussy invented (or first clearly named) a way of moving chords that composers ever since have taken up.

# Why the appendix belongs

Debussy is important not just for his own pieces, but for what he opened up. Jazz's use of ninth and thirteenth chords as stable objects — the sound of a modern jazz piano trio — is Debussy's ninth chords, taken by American musicians in the 1920s and 1930s and remade into an improvised idiom. Film scoring's use of colored chords to evoke a mood without resolution is Debussy. Modern pop songwriting's use of parallel chord motion (which shows up in songs from The Beatles' 'Because' to any number of contemporary singer-songwriter arrangements) is Debussy.

If you learn how Debussy heard chords — as objects with sonic weight rather than as steps in a progression — you can hear an enormous swath of twentieth- and twenty-first-century music with new precision.

# Sources cited

Grove Music Online, entry 'Debussy, Claude' (article by François Lesure and Roy Howat).

Simon Trezise, ed., *The Cambridge Companion to Debussy* (Cambridge University Press, 2003).

Roy Howat, *The Art of French Piano Music: Debussy, Ravel, Fauré, Chabrier* (Yale University Press, 2009).

For the 1889 gamelan encounter: Richard Mueller, 'Javanese Influence on Debussy's *Fantaisie* and Beyond,' *19th-Century Music* 10 (1986).

Scores of the Suite bergamasque, Book I of the Preludes, and other works cited are in the public domain and available on IMSLP.\"

  :notes
\"Dates and works are verifiable in Grove and Lesure. The 1889 Paris Universal Exposition and Debussy's attendance is historically documented (see Mueller article). The pentatonic-scale interpretation of Debussy's modal writing is standard scholarship. The parallel-motion violation of traditional voice-leading rules is textbook harmony. The historical influence claims (jazz, film, pop) are widely accepted in music history but stated at appropriate generality.\"

  :philosopher-weave-details
\"Wittgenstein-late: chords as words used differently — the same object (dominant seventh) means something different in Debussy than in Bach because the language-game has changed.
Peirce: the chord as icon (its sonic weight) rather than as symbol (its function in a code).
Jung: parallel motion as a single object moving through space — the chord as a whole rather than a collection of voices.\"

  :tie-forward
\"Appendix 3 will take us across the Atlantic — Ellington's swing ratio and what it does to time.\")
")
